result.execSummary:
This case is being appealed. If the court makes a decision in a case that a party disagrees with, the party may have the right to seek review by a higher court to determine if the trial court's decision was correct. Appeals are most often made after a trial or final decision in a case, but an appeal can also occur before a final decision.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Count one.
Count two.

Defendant Victor Yancey in court with Attorney Glen B. Kulkoski, as stand-by counsel.  Defendant Victor Yancey in custody.  Denis John Stingl appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Defendant has two cases before the court.
Defendant's motion for court to recuse himself denied by the Court.  Review of the counts and the penalties.

Sentencing proceeds.  Defendant disagreed with conclusions of the presentence writer; Court made notations as to items in dispute on the presentence investigation report.
State has complied with victim notification.  Statements by the State and defendant. 

As to Count 1:
Court sentenced defendant to serve 9 months in the House of Correction CONCURRENT to the sentence imposed as to Count 2; with credit for Zero days.

As to Count 2:
COURT ORDERS defendant to serve a term in the Wisconsin State Prison system - TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE -  3 years, consecutive to the sentence imposed as to Case# 14CF004078; with  Zero days credit -  INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT -  18 months  -  EXTENDED SUPERVISION -   18 months.  

Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and is NOT eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:  
-  AODA assessment and comply with any recommended treatment
-  Random screens
-  No illegal substances
-  Full-time employment
-  Court sets Restitution at $0 (zero)
-  No Contact with the co-actors
-  No firearms or dangerous weapons
-  Pay the costs, fees, assessments and surcharges during the term of extended supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

COURT ORDERS:
-  defendant to provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis (if not already done so)
-  DOC to collect monetary sums/amounts at the rate of 25% of prison funds.

Appeal rights given.  Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence and Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief received and filed.  Copies given to the defendant.

Court discharges Atty. Kulkoski.

Jury in the box at 10:00 a.m.  Court clarifies verdict forms with the panel.
At the hour of 10:05 a.m. jury left the courtroom to continue their deliberations.  Outbursts by the defendant before the jury panel exited the courtroom.
10:16 a.m.  the jury returned and by their foreperson submitted the following verdicts:

"We, the jury, find the defendant, Victor L. Yancey, Jr., GUILTY of Intimidation of a Victim (party to a crime) in the manner and form as charged in count three of the information.  Dated at Milwaukee, Wisconsin, this 7th day of January, 2016,  Signed by the foreperson."
"We, th jury, find the defendant, Victor L. Yancey, Jr., GUILTY of Attempt Bribery of Witness in the manner and form as charged in count four of the information.  Dated at Milwaukee, Wisconsin this 7th day of January, 2016.  Signed by the foreperson."
Jury polled as to their verdicts.
10:21 a.m.  Jury released from their service and out of the box.
State's motion for judgment on the verdicts granted by the Court.  Outbursts by the defendant.
Court orders a PSI.  Atty. Kulkoski to continue as stand-by counsel for the sentencing.
Court orders case adjourned for sentencing in Branch 28.    
Court ordered defendant REMANDED into the custody of the Milwaukee County Sheriff's Department, pending sentencing.
